WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.000
October 31st, 2012

00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:09.000
So, hello everyone.

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:17.000
October 31st, so probably if you think about this date, you will think about pumpkins, candies, or costumes.

00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:21.000
But October 31st is also R-Ladies' anniversary.

00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:27.000
So, the first ever R-Ladies' event took place in San Francisco on October 31st, 2012.

00:00:27.000 --> 00:00:31.000
So, this means that last year's was R-Ladies' 10th anniversary.

00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:35.000
Happy birthday!

00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:39.000
So, if you're here, you probably already know that R-Ladies' is a worldwide organization

00:00:39.000 --> 00:00:46.000
that promotes gender diversity in the art community via meetups and mentorships in a friendly and safe environment.

00:00:46.000 --> 00:00:50.000
But it started small. Only eight people showed up to the first event.

00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:52.000
It was Halloween.

00:00:52.000 --> 00:01:02.000
But today, we have 231 chapters in 63 cities, and we have organized almost 4,000 events.

00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:06.000
So, this means that the past 10 years have been years of growth.

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:11.000
And this has been possible thanks to the work of people organizing chapters around the world

00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:15.000
and R-Ladies' that engage in social media, in the Slack community,

00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:19.000
and in the different initiatives that the community organize.

00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:22.000
But it has also been possible thanks to the work of the global team,

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:29.000
the people that help us to maintain and develop our technical and social infrastructure.

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:33.000
So, our 10th year anniversary was also a moment for farewell.

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:37.000
Claudia, Erin, and Hannah stepped down as organizers. Thank you.

00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:43.000
They led us through 10 years of growth.

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:45.000
So, a new leadership was needed.

00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:49.000
And there's always people that fell into this kind of task.

00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:52.000
So, these are the five people who decided to engage with this.

00:01:52.000 --> 00:02:00.000
So, we have Mo, we have Avery, Yanni, Shannon, and me, Riva.

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:05.000
And that is why we're here today, to talk about how we're envisioning R-Ladies' next 10 years.

00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:09.000
And what we're thinking here is about how to sustain the community.

00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:14.000
How our efforts can work towards sustaining the growth of this community.

00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:16.000
So, we're people who love to code.

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:18.000
And we were thinking in the last year,

00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:23.000
what if we use good programming practices to manage our programming community?

00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:27.000
For example, modularity, refactoring, and testing.

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:29.000
So, what about modularity?

00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:32.000
You don't want a function that is that big.

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:35.000
What you want to do is to make it in small chunks,

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:40.000
so it's flexible, you can maintain it easily, and you can develop new features.

00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:42.000
So, what about communities?

00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:43.000
You want to do the same.

00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:46.000
But this is about workload, obviously.

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:49.000
You don't want just one person taking all the work.

00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:52.000
But it's not just about workload.

00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:54.000
There are other things involved.

00:02:54.000 --> 00:02:58.000
For example, if you have a team that's working on their website,

00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:01.000
and they're only working on their website, they don't have to take care about other tasks,

00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:05.000
they can focus their effort on feature development.

00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:08.000
So, making your website cooler.

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:11.000
And it's also important in terms of participation,

00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:16.000
because not everyone can engage as an organizer or as part of the global team in the same way.

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:19.000
Not everyone has the same time patterns to commit.

00:03:19.000 --> 00:03:23.000
For example, you may have some volunteers that have three hours a week

00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:26.000
that they can devote only on Friday afternoon.

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:31.000
But you have other people that prefer to work on small chunks of time.

00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:34.000
So, they can maybe go to the computer two times a day

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:37.000
and work there around 10 and 20 minutes.

00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:42.000
So, if you have a community that can offer people different ways to engage,

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:48.000
they can be part of the team and help you and all your community with the work.

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:52.000
And there are some tasks where you need people that have these time patterns.

00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:55.000
For example, you want someone moderating a community

00:03:55.000 --> 00:03:58.000
that engages not just one day, three hours,

00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:01.000
but that's there many times a week.

00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:04.000
This is also important for the ways that people can participate.

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:09.000
So, sometimes you want to participate in a community for learning new things.

00:04:09.000 --> 00:04:12.000
So, if you want to learn how to code, more about coding,

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:16.000
you might want to participate, for example, in the website team.

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:23.000
But if you want to, I don't know, engage in things that are related to social skills,

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:26.000
maybe you want to be part of the mentoring team of our ladies.

00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:29.000
So, this gives space for everyone.

00:04:29.000 --> 00:04:33.000
So, one thing that we are for sure going to keep working towards

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:35.000
is have a modular global team.

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:41.000
So, this can help everyone to participate in meaningful ways.

00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:43.000
So, what about refactoring?

00:04:43.000 --> 00:04:47.000
Sometimes you have code that works, and we want to keep it that way.

00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:49.000
We don't want to touch it.

00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:51.000
And the same happens with projects.

00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:53.000
So, sometimes you have a project that you really love,

00:04:53.000 --> 00:04:56.000
you really care about the vision of that project,

00:04:56.000 --> 00:05:01.000
and you really don't care the kind of work that involves to keep the project alive.

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:04.000
And that's because you have the vision of the project in front of you.

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:07.000
So, you're really committed to that.

00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:11.000
But it's good to think about how we can refactor our workflows

00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:16.000
as community organizers to make everyone participate in meaningful ways.

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:21.000
So, refactoring your workflows is not only about making your community more efficient,

00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:24.000
but it's also about making the time that people are committing

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:27.000
as volunteers in your community more meaningful.

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:31.000
Because you don't want people committing time that can be,

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:34.000
that's only about repetitive tasks that can be automated.

00:05:34.000 --> 00:05:37.000
You want them doing relevant things.

00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:43.000
So, as an example, we can explain what happened with the R-Ladies directory.

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:46.000
So, the R-Ladies directory is an initiative

00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:49.000
that's very related to R-Ladies mission

00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:53.000
that help us showcasing what R-Ladies do around the world.

00:05:53.000 --> 00:05:57.000
And it's an excellent antidote to all my panels.

00:05:57.000 --> 00:06:01.000
So, for example, in the directory, you can learn about,

00:06:01.000 --> 00:06:03.000
for example, if you want to engage someone in Botswana

00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:06.000
that know about computer science, there's Simi.

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:09.000
Or if you want to engage and know someone

00:06:09.000 --> 00:06:13.000
that's working in open environmental science, there's Julia.

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:16.000
Or you want to know people that are working with R in ecology,

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:18.000
you can find Benedicta.

00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:20.000
Or people that are working in health equity,

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:23.000
you can find Sylvia on the directory.

00:06:23.000 --> 00:06:29.000
So, the directory, this is how the directory used to look on the webpage.

00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:32.000
So, to add your entry to the directory,

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:35.000
you can, there's a form there that you can use.

00:06:35.000 --> 00:06:38.000
And there used to be this message.

00:06:38.000 --> 00:06:41.000
If you want to update your profile, just fill the same form

00:06:41.000 --> 00:06:46.000
and drop us a line in the comment box saying you want to update your profile.

00:06:46.000 --> 00:06:48.000
And there was this extra option.

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:52.000
Or you can just email us at speakers at rlates.org

00:06:52.000 --> 00:06:55.000
with any relevant information about yourself.

00:06:55.000 --> 00:06:57.000
Easy. Yes, easy.

00:06:57.000 --> 00:06:59.000
Because the project was starting,

00:06:59.000 --> 00:07:01.000
and what you wanted was people sending their data

00:07:01.000 --> 00:07:05.000
so you can showcase them in the directory.

00:07:05.000 --> 00:07:08.000
But what happens behind the scenes with this workflow?

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:13.000
So, you have a spreadsheet, and people start submitting their entries.

00:07:13.000 --> 00:07:17.000
And you have to take this information and put it on the website.

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:18.000
And you work in these two entries.

00:07:18.000 --> 00:07:23.000
So, you're going to put a color to remember that those are already on the website.

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:24.000
And you keep working.

00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:26.000
And then this one is not really well,

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:29.000
so you're going to work in this one afterwards.

00:07:29.000 --> 00:07:30.000
So, you put another color in there.

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:32.000
So, you remember that this one has a problem.

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:34.000
And you keep working.

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:36.000
And then you realize that this entry,

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:38.000
in the comment they put this is an update,

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:40.000
so you have to treat this one differently.

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:43.000
And then an email arrives,

00:07:43.000 --> 00:07:45.000
and you have to take the information from the email

00:07:45.000 --> 00:07:49.000
and put it here so it can go to the directory.

00:07:49.000 --> 00:07:52.000
So, this workflow worked.

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:53.000
So, it worked for years.

00:07:53.000 --> 00:07:55.000
And it could have kept working.

00:07:55.000 --> 00:07:57.000
But it has some problems.

00:07:57.000 --> 00:07:59.000
It's difficult to maintain.

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:01.000
There's a lot of space for human error.

00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:04.000
So, you don't want someone submitting their data

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:07.000
and you not uploading it to the directory.

00:08:07.000 --> 00:08:09.000
You can schedule the work.

00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:12.000
So, maybe you decide that you want to work on the directory on Fridays,

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:17.000
but you receive an email on Monday, on Tuesday, on Wednesday,

00:08:17.000 --> 00:08:20.000
about people wanting to upload their data.

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:24.000
And because you're only working on maintaining the directory,

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:26.000
you can think of feature development.

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:29.000
So, how to enhance what we have there.

00:08:29.000 --> 00:08:33.000
And this is a task that has a high risk of burnout.

00:08:33.000 --> 00:08:39.000
Because what the directory does is really awesome.

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:42.000
It helps showcase what our ladies are doing around the world.

00:08:42.000 --> 00:08:44.000
So, maybe you don't care that it's a repetitive task,

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:47.000
copy and pasting information to the website.

00:08:47.000 --> 00:08:49.000
But things happen in life.

00:08:49.000 --> 00:08:53.000
And sometimes, under certain circumstances,

00:08:53.000 --> 00:08:56.000
you're not seeing what the bigger picture is.

00:08:56.000 --> 00:08:59.000
And you realize that you're only copy-pasting information

00:08:59.000 --> 00:09:01.000
and don't understand why.

00:09:01.000 --> 00:09:06.000
And this is like the perfect recipe for burnout.

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:08.000
So, last year there was an opportunity.

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:13.000
Mo was leading the team to turn our website from WordPress to Hugo.

00:09:13.000 --> 00:09:17.000
And this was an opportunity to think again about the workflow

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:19.000
that we have for the directory.

00:09:19.000 --> 00:09:22.000
To think in a way that people can work in it,

00:09:22.000 --> 00:09:26.000
and it's meaningful, and we can end with the same result.

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:29.000
So, we still have a form. The form is there.

00:09:29.000 --> 00:09:34.000
People still submit their data through a form.

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:36.000
But now we're working with our table.

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:39.000
And now people choose an option.

00:09:39.000 --> 00:09:41.000
That's a parametric site.

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:44.000
If it's a new directory entry, if this is an update,

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:46.000
or they want to delete their entry.

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:48.000
And now we're using GitHub Actions.

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:51.000
So, GitHub Actions are a way to automate the workflow

00:09:51.000 --> 00:09:56.000
of taking the data from the form and moving it to the website.

00:09:56.000 --> 00:09:59.000
So, basically, in the directory repository,

00:09:59.000 --> 00:10:02.000
we have a folder with our actions.

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:04.000
There's the workflow. There are a lot of workflows.

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:09.000
But one is about updating, taking the data from our table

00:10:09.000 --> 00:10:11.000
and moving it to the website.

00:10:11.000 --> 00:10:16.000
This is a glimpse of the workflow.

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:19.000
But what's important here is that it runs on Friday.

00:10:19.000 --> 00:10:21.000
So, it's scheduled.

00:10:21.000 --> 00:10:26.000
So, people in the team know when the data is going to appear

00:10:26.000 --> 00:10:28.000
in the repository.

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:30.000
So, basically, what the workflow does

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:34.000
is that it takes a couple of R scripts

00:10:34.000 --> 00:10:36.000
that get the data from our table,

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:38.000
that validate the JSON files,

00:10:38.000 --> 00:10:42.000
and then the action create a pull request.

00:10:42.000 --> 00:10:45.000
GitHub Actions allowed you to customize the commit message,

00:10:45.000 --> 00:10:48.000
the branch name, the labels that you want to add,

00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:51.000
the title of your pull request.

00:10:51.000 --> 00:10:54.000
And the experience of the team at the end is very different

00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:56.000
because in the previous workflow,

00:10:56.000 --> 00:10:59.000
this is what they were dealing with.

00:10:59.000 --> 00:11:02.000
And now, on Fridays, a pull request appears

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:07.000
with all the data ready to be committed to the website.

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:15.000
So, now the task, the focus of the task is on the review,

00:11:15.000 --> 00:11:17.000
not in copy-pasting.

00:11:17.000 --> 00:11:19.000
The task can be scheduled,

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:22.000
and people have time for planning features for the website.

00:11:22.000 --> 00:11:26.000
For example, how to filter the entries that are there

00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:28.000
on some other awesome stuff that the website

00:11:28.000 --> 00:11:32.000
and the director team are always thinking about.

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:35.000
So, refactoring workflows is an opportunity also for learning.

00:11:35.000 --> 00:11:38.000
So, we like to solve problems using code.

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:41.000
So, refactoring your workflows is not extra work,

00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:43.000
but it's work that probably people in your community

00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:45.000
will want to be engaged with

00:11:45.000 --> 00:11:48.000
because they're going to learn something new about programming.

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:52.000
So, if you want to be in next Friday's pull request,

00:11:53.000 --> 00:11:57.000
you have to go to ourladies.org slash directory dash update,

00:11:57.000 --> 00:12:01.000
and your entry will be updated.

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:07.000
So, a way to discover that your workflows need

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:13.000
a little bit of refactoring is testing your workflows.

00:12:13.000 --> 00:12:19.000
So, we always want to ensure that our code behaves as expected.

00:12:19.000 --> 00:12:21.000
So, we want to do the same with our workflows.

00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:25.000
We want our workflows to behave as expected.

00:12:25.000 --> 00:12:27.000
So, I'm going to tell a little story.

00:12:27.000 --> 00:12:30.000
I became part of the global team two years ago

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:36.000
as part of the Slack monitoring team.

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:39.000
And this is a task that I jump into very easily

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:43.000
because I was already a person who was using Slack.

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:46.000
I know how the code of conduct of our ladies work

00:12:46.000 --> 00:12:48.000
because I was an organizer.

00:12:48.000 --> 00:12:52.000
So, it was very easy to me to know how to perform this task.

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:54.000
And a couple of months later,

00:12:54.000 --> 00:12:57.000
there were people needed for the meetup team,

00:12:57.000 --> 00:13:01.000
people who manage the meetup accounts of all the chapters.

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:02.000
And I fell.

00:13:02.000 --> 00:13:06.000
I wasn't able to successfully start doing this task.

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:07.000
And I was wondering why,

00:13:07.000 --> 00:13:09.000
because there's very good documentation.

00:13:09.000 --> 00:13:12.000
So, there's all the goal of the task,

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:15.000
all things that a meetup account manager needs to do

00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:17.000
was very well explained.

00:13:17.000 --> 00:13:20.000
But I didn't know how to become the person

00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:22.000
that can use the documentation.

00:13:22.000 --> 00:13:24.000
So, there was a gap between me and the documentation

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:27.000
that I didn't experience when I was working in Slack

00:13:27.000 --> 00:13:30.000
because I already was familiar with that.

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:33.000
And I discovered that the problem

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:36.000
was not with the technical infrastructure,

00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:38.000
but with the social infrastructure.

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:40.000
So, for example, to use that documentation,

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:42.000
I needed some credentials,

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:46.000
but I didn't know who I need to ask for the credentials.

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:48.000
And the person who gave the credentials

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:51.000
didn't know that I was in need of them.

00:13:51.000 --> 00:13:55.000
So, we were basically testing in production.

00:13:55.000 --> 00:13:56.000
And the problem of testing,

00:13:56.000 --> 00:13:58.000
this is absolutely valid, you can't do this.

00:13:58.000 --> 00:14:02.000
But the problem of testing in production

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:04.000
is that in some cases,

00:14:04.000 --> 00:14:07.000
what happened is something failed.

00:14:07.000 --> 00:14:09.000
And in this occasion, with perspective,

00:14:09.000 --> 00:14:12.000
I know that what failed was the workflow.

00:14:12.000 --> 00:14:14.000
But at that moment, I thought that I was failing

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:17.000
because I wasn't able to complete the task

00:14:17.000 --> 00:14:20.000
that I was expected to do.

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:22.000
So, designing onboarding processes

00:14:22.000 --> 00:14:24.000
can help you to test your community workflows

00:14:24.000 --> 00:14:26.000
and documentation.

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:28.000
This is an excellent way to realize

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:30.000
that the way that your workflows are working

00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:32.000
is what you expect.

00:14:32.000 --> 00:14:33.000
So, this is very important.

00:14:33.000 --> 00:14:37.000
This is time you want to spend in.

00:14:37.000 --> 00:14:39.000
So, I'm a serial volunteer.

00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:43.000
I'm very good at jumping into volunteers' positions.

00:14:44.000 --> 00:14:46.000
And there's another project that I participate in

00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:47.000
that's called Programming Historian,

00:14:47.000 --> 00:14:50.000
where we publish tutorials about computational tools

00:14:50.000 --> 00:14:52.000
for people in the humanities.

00:14:52.000 --> 00:14:55.000
And in this project, we have an onboarding process

00:14:55.000 --> 00:14:57.000
that's basically opening an issue

00:14:57.000 --> 00:15:01.000
and saying people how to engage with the project.

00:15:01.000 --> 00:15:03.000
We have very good documentation.

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:06.000
So, all the tasks that people need to know are there.

00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:10.000
But we onboard people because we need them

00:15:10.000 --> 00:15:14.000
to become the person that can use the documentation.

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:16.000
So, in this issue that we open,

00:15:16.000 --> 00:15:20.000
we welcome people because we're nice.

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:22.000
We explain what the project will do,

00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:25.000
what the programming team will do to onboard you.

00:15:25.000 --> 00:15:29.000
We explain people what they should do to be onboarded.

00:15:29.000 --> 00:15:34.000
And that allows us to people

00:15:34.000 --> 00:15:37.000
becoming part of the team with no problem.

00:15:37.000 --> 00:15:41.000
So, at Our Ladies, we start designing onboarding processes.

00:15:41.000 --> 00:15:47.000
This is the first one where we try to explicitly mention the task.

00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:49.000
It has three hearts.

00:15:49.000 --> 00:15:54.000
But this first version has a very complicated problem.

00:15:54.000 --> 00:15:56.000
We hard-coded things.

00:15:56.000 --> 00:15:58.000
We hard-coded people's names.

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:02.000
And you never hard-code people's names on your documentation.

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:04.000
Because, for example, last week,

00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:08.000
we discovered that Hannah was stealing our documentation.

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:12.000
And people were going to ask her to create GitHub repositories.

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:14.000
And we want Hannah working on tidy models,

00:16:14.000 --> 00:16:17.000
not creating repositories for other people.

00:16:17.000 --> 00:16:22.000
So, now we are improving our onboarding processes.

00:16:22.000 --> 00:16:26.000
And now we only mention teams because it's easier to maintain.

00:16:26.000 --> 00:16:29.000
So, every time we onboard a new member,

00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:33.000
we discover new ways to improve our documentation and our workflows.

00:16:33.000 --> 00:16:36.000
And we're going to keep working on that.

00:16:36.000 --> 00:16:38.000
So, obviously, we ask ourselves,

00:16:38.000 --> 00:16:41.000
what if we automate part of the process?

00:16:41.000 --> 00:16:44.000
So, now we have a GitHub action

00:16:44.000 --> 00:16:49.000
that we dispatch it by running our workflow manually.

00:16:49.000 --> 00:16:54.000
And what we do is that we put the team that the person is getting onboard,

00:16:54.000 --> 00:16:57.000
the name of the person, and their GitHub handle.

00:16:57.000 --> 00:16:59.000
And when we run this workflow,

00:16:59.000 --> 00:17:02.000
what is going to happen very fast

00:17:02.000 --> 00:17:06.000
is that it will take our issue template.

00:17:06.000 --> 00:17:10.000
It will take the information from the inputs that we put there.

00:17:10.000 --> 00:17:14.000
We will get the user ID, check if it's already in our organization,

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:16.000
invite the user to the organization,

00:17:16.000 --> 00:17:18.000
wait for the user to accept the invitation,

00:17:18.000 --> 00:17:22.000
add the user to the corresponding GitHub team,

00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:25.000
combine the templates, and replace placeholder,

00:17:25.000 --> 00:17:29.000
and finally create an issue to welcome someone new to the global team.

00:17:29.000 --> 00:17:32.000
So, that's all you have to click some buttons,

00:17:32.000 --> 00:17:35.000
and the template is there.

00:17:35.000 --> 00:17:37.000
So, as we said before, we love coding.

00:17:37.000 --> 00:17:39.000
And in this past year, we've been thinking

00:17:39.000 --> 00:17:42.000
how we can use these good programming practices

00:17:42.000 --> 00:17:46.000
to improve the work that we're doing at Ladies' Global.

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:49.000
And the takeaways here is that designing a model community

00:17:49.000 --> 00:17:51.000
is a good way to distribute work,

00:17:51.000 --> 00:17:53.000
and to distribute work in a meaningful way.

00:17:53.000 --> 00:17:55.000
Refactor your workflows.

00:17:55.000 --> 00:17:57.000
It's important to avoid repetitive tasks.

00:17:57.000 --> 00:18:00.000
And on the long run, make your process easier to maintain

00:18:00.000 --> 00:18:02.000
and avoid burnout.

00:18:02.000 --> 00:18:04.000
And creating onboarding processes is a good way

00:18:04.000 --> 00:18:08.000
to test your technical and social infrastructure

00:18:08.000 --> 00:18:11.000
to keep all your processes run smoothly.

00:18:11.000 --> 00:18:15.000
So, let's bring the joy of programming to our community management,

00:18:15.000 --> 00:18:18.000
and hope you can take some of these ideas

00:18:18.000 --> 00:18:21.000
and put them in practices on your own communities.

00:18:21.000 --> 00:18:23.000
Thank you.

00:18:23.000 --> 00:18:25.000
Thank you.

00:18:32.000 --> 00:18:33.000
All right, Reva.

00:18:33.000 --> 00:18:36.000
In the last 30 seconds, can you say anything

00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:40.000
about how you're handling knowledge transfer

00:18:40.000 --> 00:18:42.000
as you're going through leadership transitions?

00:18:42.000 --> 00:18:44.000
That's a very good question.

00:18:44.000 --> 00:18:48.000
So, a couple of years ago,

00:18:48.000 --> 00:18:51.000
the Art Consortium helped us to finance

00:18:51.000 --> 00:18:53.000
creating our Ladies' Guide.

00:18:53.000 --> 00:18:56.000
So, we have a knowledge base that is available for everyone.

00:18:56.000 --> 00:18:58.000
So, the transition,

00:18:58.000 --> 00:19:00.000
so in terms of knowledge about the organization,

00:19:00.000 --> 00:19:04.000
we have that as a knowledge base.

00:19:04.000 --> 00:19:06.000
So, I think the most difficult things

00:19:06.000 --> 00:19:08.000
have been like bureaucratic things

00:19:08.000 --> 00:19:10.000
that are involved in an organization like that.

00:19:10.000 --> 00:19:12.000
Banks, for example.

00:19:12.000 --> 00:19:14.000
Banks.

00:19:14.000 --> 00:19:16.000
Okay. Fantastic. Let's thank Reva again.

00:19:16.000 --> 00:19:18.000
Thank you.

